<a href="https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipados-26/">iPadOS 26</a> is going to change the way that you use your <a href="https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad/">iPad</a>, and it turns working on the &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; into a much more Mac-like experience. Apple introduced a whole new multitasking system, which you can get a first look at in our video.<br/>
<br/>
<div class="center-wrap"><iframe title="Hands-On with iPadOS 26: New Mac-Like Features &amp; Multitasking!" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/P1wBldurXeI" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe><em><a href="https://www.youtube.com/user/macrumors?sub_confirmation=1">Subscribe to the MacRumors YouTube channel</a> for more videos.</em></div><br/>
Windows on the &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; now work like Windows on the Mac. You can have multiple app windows open at once, and arrange them in any way that's convenient for you. Split View and Slide Over are gone, but the new window options work with <a href="https://www.macrumors.com/guide/stage-manager/">Stage Manager</a>.<br/>
<br/>
&zwnj;iPad&zwnj; apps have menu bars where you can access settings for each app, and there are also the iconic "traffic light" buttons that you can use for adjusting and resizing open windows. Apple added multiple convenient tiling options for showing two, three, or four apps on your display in an organized way. You can view all of your open apps with an Expos√© interface.<br/>
<br/>
The windowing system extends to connected displays, giving you even more space for viewing your &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; apps. Note that on some older iPads, you'll be limited to four app windows, but this is a feature that is compatible with every &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; that runs &zwnj;iPadOS 26&zwnj;. Newer iPads can have far more app windows open.<br/>
<br/>
To further the Mac-like experience, folders are now customizable with colors and emoji, and in the Files app, there's a new list view that's like working with the Mac files app. Apple even added collapsible folders, so you don't need to tap into a folder on &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; to see what's inside in a tiled view.<br/>
<br/>
Files can be set to open with a default app of your choosing, and you can store your folders in the Dock for quicker access. Finally, the &zwnj;iPad&zwnj; supports background tasks, so if you're doing a large file transfer, you'll see a Live Activity to keep an eye on progress while you do other things on your &zwnj;iPad&zwnj;.<br/>
<br/>
Keep in mind that we're only on the first beta of &zwnj;iPadOS 26&zwnj;, and there's more testing and refining to go before launch. Right now, &zwnj;iPadOS 26&zwnj; is only available for developers, but Apple is going to make a public beta available in July. &zwnj;iPadOS 26&zwnj; will launch in September.<div class="linkback">Related Roundups: <a href="https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ios-26/">iOS 26</a>, <a href="https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipados-26/">iPadOS 26</a></div><div class="linkback">Related Forum: <a href="https://forums.macrumors.com/forums/ios-26.248">iOS 26</a></div><br/>This article, &quot;<a href="https://www.macrumors.com/2025/06/17/ipados-26-multitasking/">See iPadOS 26 Multitasking in Action</a>&quot; first appeared on <a href="https://www.macrumors.com">MacRumors.com</a><br/><br/><a href="https://forums.macrumors.com/threads/see-ipados-26-multitasking-in-action.2459183/">Discuss this article</a> in our forums<br/><br/>